body: Thanks for reporting this. Is your finding consistent with other frameworks? Or the onnx tests?

Yes I checked onnx tests, pytorch and tensorflow.
In all of these cases they use 5D input for 3d convolutions and pooling.
In the onnxruntime tests I linked above padding might be invalid because there should be 6 zeros(above and below each axis) and in these tests there are 9 zeros.
Gathered data:
ONNX python unit tests input shapes:
convtranspose_3d: `[1, 1, 3, 4, 5]` and `[1, 2, 3, 3, 3]`
averagepool_3d: `[1, 3, 32, 32, 32]`
maxpool_3d: `[1, 3, 32, 32, 32]`
pytorch-converted.avg_pool_3d: `[2, 3, 4, 4, 4]`
pytorch-converted.conv_3d: `[2, 3, 3, 4, 5]`

pytorch conv3d: https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/nn.html#id22
pytorch conv-transpose3d: https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/nn.html#conv-transpose3d
tensorflow conv3d: https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/nn/conv3d
tensorflow conv3d_transpose: https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/nn/conv3d_transpose
@tsocha - Thanks for reporting this. Yes, that seems right. It doesn't look like a "3D" test case as the test name suggests. Let me add some real "3D" test cases :).

issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
The [ConvTranspose Operator](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#ConvTranspose) supports inputs of size N x C x D1 x D2 x ... x Dn

Unfortunately, onnxruntime errors for inputs with anything other than 2D ConvTranspose (input N x C x H x W):

`RuntimeError: Method run failed due to: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 2 : INVALID_ARGUMENT : Input X must be 4-dimensional.`

This seems to originate from:
https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/0ad940027c0b93e971663cdf3fbcc83eb10b7b5b/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/nn/conv_transpose.cc#L93

It is mentioned that 3D ConvTranspose is not implemented yet in Issue #699.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): 0.3.0

**Describe the solution you'd like**
I would like to request support for 3D ConvTranspose, e.g. input (N x C x H x W x D) and weights (C x M/group x kH x kW x kD), where M is feature maps. 

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
None considered

**Additional context**
N/A
